issue.title: Hokuyo link not spinning in Rviz

content.raw:
The output for rostopic echo -c /multisense/lidar_scan has all ranges at -INF and intensities at 1.0. The header information is constant from scan to scan.

In Gazebo the lidar is moving.

```
#!c++


Ubuntu version: 14.04.5 LTS
Gazebo version: 7.4.0
ROS version: Indigo
```

issue.title: Hokuyo link not spinning in Rviz

content.html:
I'm not sure what you exactly mean by that but the lidar_scan does report different distances as it (theoretically should be) spins, rviz also shows changing laser ranges over time. The only thing is that spinning is seen in gazebo and not rviz. So what I get is a horizontal laser range that changes as if it were spinning but it only stays constantly horizontal.

issue.title: Hokuyo link not spinning in Rviz

content.raw:
Okay I figured out the source of error. For some reason the topic 
```
#!

/ihmc_ros/valkyrie/output/joint_state
```
Shows that the Hokuyo link's position is always 0.0 despite that it's actually spinning. I decided to import some drcsim code that would create a node to report multisense joint states:

```
#!

  <node pkg="robot_state_publisher" type="state_publisher" name="multisense_robot_state_publisher">
    <param name="publish_frequency" type="double" value="50.0" />
    <remap from="joint_states" to="/multisense/joint_states" />
  </node>
```
Then the hokuyo joint started to actually sort of spin in rviz. Checking the topic:

```
#!

/multisense/joint_states
```
I verified that this does indeed give the correct hokuyo position instead of the ihmc topic. The only issue I have right now is that because both the multisense and ihmc joints states are being subscribed by rviz, it gets confused whether the joint is either spinning (multisense topic) or (ihmc topic) becomes stationed at horizontal. What I ultimately get is a half spinning laser range that glitches to horizontal then back to spinning where it left off. Is there a way to fix the IHMC's joint_state publisher so that the hokuyo joint reflects it's gazebo counterpart?
content.html:
Okay I figured out the source of error. For some reason the topic 

/ihmc_ros/valkyrie/output/joint_state

Shows that the Hokuyo link's position is always 0.0 despite that it's actually spinning. I decided to import some drcsim code that would create a node to report multisense joint states:

  <node pkg="robot_state_publisher" type="state_publisher" name="multisense_robot_state_publisher">
    <param name="publish_frequency" type="double" value="50.0" />
    <remap from="joint_states" to="/multisense/joint_states" />
  </node>

Then the hokuyo joint started to actually sort of spin in rviz. Checking the topic:

/multisense/joint_states

I verified that this does indeed give the correct hokuyo position instead of the ihmc topic. The only issue I have right now is that because both the multisense and ihmc joints states are being subscribed by rviz, it gets confused whether the joint is either spinning (multisense topic) or (ihmc topic) becomes stationed at horizontal. What I ultimately get is a half spinning laser range that glitches to horizontal then back to spinning where it left off. Is there a way to fix the IHMC's joint_state publisher so that the hokuyo joint reflects it's gazebo counterpart?

content.raw:
Kudos to WPI Robotics Lab for providing this information on the fix for the lidar!
Quote from their team member Vinayak Jagtap:

Posting this again as a separate message for the benefit of those who are interested. To get the lidar spinning modify the robot_description_common.launch file present in ihmc_ros_common package to have the following :

```
#!

<node name="joint_state_publisher" pkg="joint_state_publisher" type="joint_state_publisher">
<param name="use_gui" value="FALSE"/> 
<rosparam param="/source_list">[/multisense/joint_states, /hardware_joint_states]</rosparam> 
</node>
<node name="robot_state_publisher" pkg="robot_state_publisher" type="robot_state_publisher" >
<!-- remap from="joint_states" to="/ihmc_ros/$(arg robot_name)/output/joint_states" / -->
<remap from="robot_description" to="/$(arg robot_name)/robot_description" />
</node>
```
